es of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Erneys Sr was born about 1287, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Richard de Erneys. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1287–":"umbes 1287–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1310–1379":"1310–1379","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","1379":"1379","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1262":"1262","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1287–":"noin 1287–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1310–1379":"1310–1379","1262–Male":"1262–Kuollut","1379":"1379","Abt 1287":"noin 1287","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1262":"1262","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1287–":"environ 1287–Décédé","1287–Male":"1287–Décédé","1310–1379":"1310–1379","1262–Male":"1262–Décédé","1379":"1379","Abt 1287":"environ 1287","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1262":"1262","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert Erneys Sr est né environ 1287, à Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Richard d’Erneys. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Abt 1287–":"um 1287–Verstorbe